{"title_page": "Ivan Mikhailovich Simonov", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Ivan Mikhailovich Simonov\n|image             = Simonov Ivan Mikh-ch astronomer c1850.jpg\n|image_size        = 225px\n|caption           = I. M. Simonov \u2014 rector of Kazan University ([[Daguerreotype]], about 1850 y.)\n|birth_date        = June 20 (July 1), 1794\n|birth_place       = Astrakhan, [[Russian Empire]]\n|death_date        = Jan. 10 (22), 1855\n|death_place       = Kazan\n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = Kazan\n|nationality       = [[Russians]]\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = [[Astronomy]]\n|work_institutions = [[Kazan State University]]\n|alma_mater        = \n|doctoral_advisor  = \n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = discovering Antarctica\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = \n|religion          = \n|footnotes         = \n|signature         =\n}}\n'''Ivan Mikhailovich Simonov''' (1794\u20131855)<ref name=\"Barratt1988\">{{cite book|author=Glynn Barratt|title=The Russians and Australia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bE2aGbVyugkC&pg=PA146-IA12|accessdate=26 June 2013|date=1 January 1988|publisher=[[UBC Press]]|isbn=978-0-7748-4316-4|pages=146\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Lobachevski\u012d2010\">{{cite book|author=N. Nikola\u012d Ivanovich Lobachevski\u012d|title=Pangeometry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p15epMkyx0UC&pg=PA213|accessdate=26 June 2013|date=1 January 2010|publisher=[[European Mathematical Society]]|isbn=978-3-03719-087-6|pages=213\u2013}}</ref> was a Russian astronomer and a geodesist.\n\n==Biography==\nHe completed his studies and became a professor of physics at [[Kazan State University]] in 1816<ref name=\"The Great Soviet Encyclopedia\">{{cite web|title=Simonov, Ivan Mikhailovich|url=http://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Simonov,+Ivan+Mikhailovich|publisher=[[The Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]}}</ref> where he was a close friend of [[Nikolai Lobachevsky]].<ref name=\"Lobachevski\u012d2010\" /> He was a corresponding member of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Saint Petersburg Academy of Sciences]] from 1829 and later went on to become the rector of [[Kazan State University]] in 1846.<ref name=\"Barratt1988\" />\n\nFrom 1819 to 1821 he took part in and wrote a detailed account of F. F. Bellingshausen and M. P. La-zarev\u2019s expedition around the world, during which the continent of Antarctica was discovered.<br />\nAmong Simonov\u2019s contributions are his many astronomical observations, the development of methods for such observations, and the design of a reflector. Simonov was among the first in Russia to study terrestrial magnetism. On his initiative two observatories were established in Kazan: an astronomical observatory in 1833 and an observatory for the study of magnetism in 1843. Simonov Island (Tuvana-I-Tholo) in the South Pacific and the northeastern cape of Peter I Island were named in Simonov\u2019s honor.<ref name=\"The Great Soviet Encyclopedia\"/>\n\n==Childhood. Study. Youth==\nHe was born in Astrakhan` city with nobles family in 20 June 1794. To 1808 studied in Astrakhan` province gymnasium, then entered the Kazan gymnasium. In 1809, he started studying at Imperial Kazan University. After graduated in 1810 Simonov right away pass exam for scientific Bachelor degree by physical and mathematical science.\nThe World Trip\nIn 1819 with offer from Science Academy Simonov was assigned astronomer at The World Trip in southern hemisphere with boats \u201cVostok\u201d and \u201cMirniy\u201d. This expedition in a first time discovered shelf ice of the south polar continent \u2013 Antarctica\nSimonov is the first Russian astronomer who have deal with The World Trip. He make the first observations of stars in the southern hemisphere of the sky, what was not able to discover in Russia. Moreover, he was single scientist in this mission. In addition to astronomic observations and detection geographical coordinates, he was conducting magnetic observations and for the first time claimed South magnetic pole of the Earth is located at 76\u00b0 South and 142.5\u00b0 West (since then, its position has changed significantly due to the age-old displacement of the magnetic poles).\n\n==Work And Life==\nAfter return to Kazan in 1822, he was confirmed as an ordinary Professor of astronomy. In 1822-1823 and 1825-1830-Dean of the faculty of physics and mathematics of Kazan University.\nIn 1828, he toured a significant part of the Kazan province and part of Simbirsk and Orenburg, where by astronomical observations he established the exact geographical coordinates of many cities, and with the help of a barometer he determined at what height the places he visited were located.\nAt the initiative of I. M. Simonov, two observatories were founded in Kazan \u2014 the astronomical one, of which he was Director in 1838-1855, and the magnetic one (1843).\n\n==Memory==\n\u2022\tSimonov`s island in the Pacific ocean, the southernmost in the Lau island group (Fiji); its local name is Tuvana-Itolo.\n\n\u2022\tSimonov glacier (Norv. Simonovbreen) on the Antarctic island of [[Peter the Great]].\n\n\u2022\tSimonov was buried in the Kizichesky cemetery in Kazan, which was destroyed during the Soviet Union period. In 2010, a memorial stone was installed in the Kizichesky monastery at the conditional burial place of I. M. Simonov\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simonov, Ivan Mikhailovich}}\n[[Category:1794 births]]\n[[Category:1855 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kazan]]\n[[Category:Russian astronomers]]\n[[Category:Russian geodesists]]\n[[Category:Kazan (Volga region) Federal University]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Ivan Mikhailovich Simonov\n|image             = Simonov Ivan Mikh-ch astronomer c1850.jpg\n|image_size        = 225px\n|caption           = I. M. Simonov \u2014 rector of Kazan University ([[Daguerreotype]], about 1850 y.)\n|birth_date        = June 20 (July 1), 1794\n|birth_place       = Astrakhan, [[Russian Empire]]\n|death_date        = Jan. 10 (22), 1855\n|death_place       = Kazan\n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = Kazan\n|nationality       = [[Russians]]\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = [[Astronomy]]\n|work_institutions = [[Kazan State University]]\n|alma_mater        = \n|doctoral_advisor  = \n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = discovering Antarctica\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = \n|religion          = \n|footnotes         = \n|signature         =\n}}\n'''Ivan Mikhailovich Simonov''' (1794\u20131855)<ref name=\"Barratt1988\">{{cite book|author=Glynn Barratt|title=The Russians and Australia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bE2aGbVyugkC&pg=PA146-IA12|accessdate=26 June 2013|date=1 January 1988|publisher=[[UBC Press]]|isbn=978-0-7748-4316-4|pages=146\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Lobachevski\u012d2010\">{{cite book|author=N. Nikola\u012d Ivanovich Lobachevski\u012d|title=Pangeometry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p15epMkyx0UC&pg=PA213|accessdate=26 June 2013|date=1 January 2010|publisher=[[European Mathematical Society]]|isbn=978-3-03719-087-6|pages=213\u2013}}</ref> was a Russian astronomer and a geodesist.\n\n==Biography==\nHe completed his studies and became a professor of physics at [[Kazan State University]] in 1816<ref name=\"The Great Soviet Encyclopedia\">{{cite web|title=Simonov, Ivan Mikhailovich|url=http://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Simonov,+Ivan+Mikhailovich|publisher=[[The Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]}}</ref> where he was a close friend of [[Nikolai Lobachevsky]].<ref name=\"Lobachevski\u012d2010\" /> He was a corresponding member of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Saint Petersburg Academy of Sciences]] from 1829 and later went on to become the rector of [[Kazan State University]] in 1846.<ref name=\"Barratt1988\" />\n\nFrom 1819 to 1821 he took part in and wrote a detailed account of F. F. Bellingshausen and M. P. La-zarev\u2019s expedition around the world, during which the continent of Antarctica was discovered.<br />\nAmong Simonov\u2019s contributions are his many astronomical observations, the development of methods for such observations, and the design of a reflector. Simonov was among the first in Russia to study terrestrial magnetism. On his initiative two observatories were established in Kazan: an astronomical observatory in 1833 and an observatory for the study of magnetism in 1843. Simonov Island (Tuvana-I-Tholo) in the South Pacific and the northeastern cape of Peter I Island were named in Simonov\u2019s honor.<ref name=\"The Great Soviet Encyclopedia\"/>\n\n\n==Childhood. Study. Youth==\nHe was born in Astrakhan` city with nobles family in 20 June 1794. To 1808 studied in Astrakhan` province gymnasium, then entered the Kazan gymnasium. In 1809, he started studying at Imperial Kazan University. After graduated in 1810 Simonov right away pass exam for scientific Bachelor degree by physical and mathematical science.\nThe World Trip\nIn 1819 with offer from Science Academy Simonov was assigned astronomer at The World Trip in southern hemisphere with boats \u201cVostok\u201d and \u201cMirniy\u201d. This expedition in a first time discovered shelf ice of the south polar continent \u2013 Antarctica\nSimonov is the first Russian astronomer who have deal with The World Trip. He make the first observations of stars in the southern hemisphere of the sky, what was not able to discover in Russia. Moreover, he was single scientist in this mission. In addition to astronomic observations and detection geographical coordinates, he was conducting magnetic observations and for the first time claimed South magnetic pole of the Earth is located at 76\u00b0 South and 142.5\u00b0 West (since then, its position has changed significantly due to the age-old displacement of the magnetic poles).\n\n==Work And Life==\nAfter return to Kazan in 1822, he was confirmed as an ordinary Professor of astronomy. In 1822-1823 and 1825-1830-Dean of the faculty of physics and mathematics of Kazan University.\nIn 1828, he toured a significant part of the Kazan province and part of Simbirsk and Orenburg, where by astronomical observations he established the exact geographical coordinates of many cities, and with the help of a barometer he determined at what height the places he visited were located.\nAt the initiative of I. M. Simonov, two observatories were founded in Kazan \u2014 the astronomical one, of which he was Director in 1838-1855, and the magnetic one (1843).\n\n==Memory==\n\u2022\tSimonov`s island in the Pacific ocean, the southernmost in the Lau island group (Fiji); its local name is Tuvana-Itolo.\n\n\u2022\tSimonov glacier (Norv. Simonovbreen) on the Antarctic island of [[Peter the Great|| Peter the Great]].\n\n\u2022\tSimonov was buried in the Kizichesky cemetery in Kazan, which was destroyed during the Soviet Union period. In 2010, a memorial stone was installed in the Kizichesky monastery at the conditional burial place of I. M. Simonov\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simonov, Ivan Mikhailovich}}\n[[Category:1794 births]]\n[[Category:1855 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kazan]]\n[[Category:Russian astronomers]]\n[[Category:Russian geodesists]]\n[[Category:Kazan (Volga region) Federal University]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Double pipe in a link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivan_Mikhailovich_Simonov"}
{"title_page": "Lot quality assurance sampling", "text_new": "'''Lot quality assurance sampling (LQAS)''' is a [[random sampling]] methodology, originally developed in the 1920s <ref name=\"DodgeRomig1929\">{{cite journal | last1 = Dodge | first1 = H.F. | last2 = Romig | first2 = H.G. | year = 1929 | title = A method of sampling inspection | url = https://archive.org/details/bstj8-4-613 | journal = Bell System Technical Journal | volume = 8 | issue = | pages = 613\u201331 }}</ref> as a method of [[quality control]] in industrial production. Compared to similar sampling techniques like [[stratified sampling|stratified]] and [[cluster sampling]], LQAS provides less information but often requires substantially smaller sample sizes.\n\n==Summary==\nLQAS, sometimes called \"acceptance sampling\",<ref name=\"LemeshowTaber1991\">{{cite journal | last1 = Lemeshow | first1 = S. | last2 = Taber | first2 = S. | year = 1991 | title = Lot quality assurance sampling: single- and double-sampling plans | url = | journal = World Health Statistics Quarterly | volume = 44 | issue = 3| pages = 115\u201332 | pmid = 1949879 }}</ref> involves taking a small [[random sample]] from each set of items in the population, and testing each sampled item to determine whether it meets a predetermined standard of quality. LQAS is functionally identical to [[stratified sampling]] (where each lot is a single stratum), but requires smaller samples because it does not attempt to construct a precise estimate of population parameters. Instead, after sampling, a researcher using LQAS performs a [[Statistical inference|hypothesis test]] to determine whether the number of elements of interest in each lot (e.g. defective units in manufacturing, or persons with a particular medical condition in epidemiology) is likely to be greater than a predetermined threshold.\n\n==Use==\nLQAS was originally designed for use in manufacturing, where it provided a way to perform statistically valid quality-assurance testing at minimum cost. In the context of modern research, LQAS has become an accepted sampling method in the fields of public health and international development. For example, in 1996 the [[World Health Organization]] issued a document<ref name=\"WHO1996\">Robertson, S. (1996). [http://extranet.who.int/ivb_docs/documents/1049 ''Monitoring immunization services using the Lot Quality Technique.''] World Health Organization: Geneva.</ref> describing LQAS, and recommended it for use in surveys to determine the number of children immunized against disease.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Alberti | first1 = K.P. | last2 = Guthmann | first2 = J.P. | last3 = Fermon | first3 = F. | last4 = Nargaye | first4 = K.D. | last5 = Grais | first5 = R.F. | year = 2008 | title = Use of Lot Quality Assurance Sampling (LQAS) to estimate vaccination coverage helps guide future vaccination efforts | url = | journal = Transactions of the Royal Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene | volume = 102 | issue = 3| pages = 251\u20134 }}\n*{{Cite journal | last1 = Biedron | first1 = C. | last2 = Pagano | first2 = M. | last3 = Hedt | first3 = B. L. | last4 = Kilian | first4 = A. | last5 = Ratcliffe | first5 = A. | last6 = Mabunda | first6 = S. | last7 = Valadez | first7 = J. J. | doi = 10.1093/ije/dyp363 | title = An assessment of Lot Quality Assurance Sampling to evaluate malaria outcome indicators: Extending malaria indicator surveys | journal = International Journal of Epidemiology | volume = 39 | issue = 1 | pages = 72\u201379 | year = 2010 | pmid =  20139435| pmc =2912491 }}\n\n[[Category:Quality assurance]]\n[[Category:Sampling (statistics)]]\n\n\n{{statistics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Lot quality assurance sampling (LQAS)''' is a [[random sampling]] methodology, originally developed in the 1920s <ref name=\"DodgeRomig1929\">Dodge, H.F., & Romig, H.G. (1929). [https://archive.org/details/bstj8-4-613 \"A method of sampling inspection.\"] ''Bell System Technical Journal'' 8: 613\u201331.</ref> as a method of [[quality control]] in industrial production. Compared to similar sampling techniques like [[stratified sampling|stratified]] and [[cluster sampling]], LQAS provides less information but often requires substantially smaller sample sizes.\n\n==Summary==\nLQAS, sometimes called \"acceptance sampling\",<ref name=\"LemeshowTaber1991\">Lemeshow, S. & Taber, S. (1991). Lot quality assurance sampling: single- and double-sampling plans\". ''World Health Statistics Quarterly'', 44(3), 115-32. {{PMID|1949879}}</ref> involves taking a small [[random sample]] from each set of items in the population, and testing each sampled item to determine whether it meets a predetermined standard of quality. LQAS is functionally identical to [[stratified sampling]] (where each lot is a single stratum), but requires smaller samples because it does not attempt to construct a precise estimate of population parameters. Instead, after sampling, a researcher using LQAS performs a [[Statistical inference|hypothesis test]] to determine whether the number of elements of interest in each lot (e.g. defective units in manufacturing, or persons with a particular medical condition in epidemiology) is likely to be greater than a predetermined threshold.\n\n==Use==\nLQAS was originally designed for use in manufacturing, where it provided a way to perform statistically valid quality-assurance testing at minimum cost. In the context of modern research, LQAS has become an accepted sampling method in the fields of public health and international development. For example, in 1996 the [[World Health Organization]] issued a document<ref name=\"WHO1996\">Robertson, S. (1996). [http://extranet.who.int/ivb_docs/documents/1049 ''Monitoring immunization services using the Lot Quality Technique.''] World Health Organization: Geneva.</ref> describing LQAS, and recommended it for use in surveys to determine the number of children immunized against disease.\n\n==Notes==